## 4. `lcc=True` silently deletes 982 drugs (5.9% of the drug universe)

The how-to's A1 uses `load_graph(lcc=True)`. Measured cost:

| | full | LCC | dropped |
|---|---|---|---|
| nodes | 190,531 | 189,364 | 1,167 (0.61%) |
| edges | 21,813,816 | 21,812,730 | 1,086 (0.005%) |

Dropped nodes by label:

| label | dropped | of total | rate |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DRG` | 982 | 16,766 | **5.86%** |
| `PHE` | 164 | 19,341 | 0.85% |
| `DIS` | 15 | 36,345 | 0.04% |
| `EXP` | 6 | 881 | 0.68% |

No ontology-backed type (`GEN`, `ANA`, `BPO`, `CCO`, `MFN`, `PWY`) is dropped —
they hang off `IS_A`/`PARENT` hierarchies and cannot be orphaned. Only
evidence-attached entity types fall out. The 164 `PHE` are exactly the
`meddra`-prefixed nodes. Fewer edges than nodes dropped ⇒ ≥81 separate
components outside the LCC, many nodes fully isolated.

**Decision: `graph_variant = "full"`** (`data/manifest/a1_decisions.json`, frozen).

Not because those 982 drugs are usable — an edgeless node is unreachable to a
path-retrieval agent either way — but because **full makes the exclusion visible
and countable**. Under `full`, they fall out at A6/A7 where coverage is reported.
Under LCC they vanish before anything can count them, and a repoDB gold positive
involving one just quietly doesn't exist. The how-to requires reporting coverage
honestly; you cannot report what was deleted upstream.

Downstream steps read `source_tables` from `a1_decisions.json`, not hardcoded
filenames.

