## 5. The how-to's schema assumptions are wrong (A2 will KeyError)

| how-to assumes | release 2.0 actually has |
|---|---|
| nodes: `id`, `category`, `name`, `description` | **`id`, `label`, `properties`** |
| edges: `subject`, `predicate`, `object`, `provided_by` | **`from`, `to`, `label`, `relation`, `undirected`, `properties`** |
| Biolink predicates (`treats`) | codes: `INDICATION`, `ASSOCIATED_WITH`, `EXPRESSION_PRESENT` |
| provenance in `provided_by` | **`properties.sources.{direct,indirect}`** — lists, not a scalar |
| "predicates are directional; preserve direction" | explicit **`undirected` boolean per edge** — and `DRG-DIS` is `undirected: true` |
| "26 relation types" | **27 edge labels, 36 distinct relations** |

`canon_nodes = nodes.select(id_curie=pl.col("id"), category=..., name=...,
description=...)` **fails as written**. Rewrite A2 against `okg_census.json`.

In the flat tables `properties` is a **JSON string**; in the stratified per-type
files it is a native Polars **Struct**. Prefer stratified where the file is
checksum-verified (drug, disease, drug_disease, drug_gene, disease_gene,
drug_phenotype, drug_biological_process, phenotype_gene); use the flat tables
otherwise.

**On the docs site:** optimuskg.ai documents release **1.0**. Its "26 relation
types" (PyPI) / "27 edge types" (docs) both count *labels*; PyPI's figure is
simply wrong. Use `okg_census.json` as the sole schema reference.

