## 8. The A7 leakage surface is 7 label/relation pairs, not 1

From `okg_census.json` — **79,949 edges total**:

| label | relation | edges |
|---|---|---|
| `DRG-DIS` | `INDICATION` | 57,601 |
| `DRG-DIS` | `CONTRAINDICATION` | 11,718 |
| `DRG-DIS` | `OFF_LABEL_USE` | 1,061 |
| `DRG-PHE` | `CONTRAINDICATION` | 8,279 |
| `DRG-PHE` | `INDICATION` | 1,027 |
| `DRG-PHE` | `OFF_LABEL_USE` | 201 |
| `DRG-BPO` | `INDICATION` | 62 |

`DRG-PHE` is exactly the "shortcut duplicate" the how-to warns about: diseases and
phenotypes overlap heavily, so a held-out drug→disease pair can leak through a
drug→phenotype edge. Stripping only `DRG-DIS/INDICATION` leaves **22,348 edges**
of leakage surface behind.

**Possible circularity — investigate at A5/A7.** `DRG-DIS` edges carry
`properties.structure_id` and `drug_disease_id` (DrugCentral identifiers), so
OptimusKG's indication edges appear to be DrugCentral-derived. repoDB is also
built on DrugCentral. The gold set and the graph's own indication edges may be
near-duplicates rather than independent. This does not invalidate the design —
A7 removes those edges by construction — but it must be stated in the writeup,
and it means "evaluable positives" coverage will look artificially high.
